record_data.record_plain_text: Preamble This FOURTH AMENDED AND RESTATED USE AGREEMENT (“Use Agreement”), dated as of November 1, 2020 and effective as of the Effective Date (as provided for in Section 4 of this Use Agreement) amends and restates a certain agreement with respect to the use of the Quebec-United States transmission interconnection, originally dated as of December 1, 1981, amended and restated as of September 1, 1985, and November 19, 1997, and further amended as of April 8, 1998, June 29, 2001 and February 11, 2002 (the “Initial Agreement”). This Use Agreement is among the entities listed in Attachment A hereto (the “Phase I Interconnection Rights Holders”) and Attachment B hereto (the “Phase II Interconnection Rights Holders”), which are parties to this Use Agreement and which hold the exclusive rights to use the Interconnection. Collectively, the Phase I Interconnection Rights Holders and the Phase II Interconnection Rights Holders are the “Parties”. Recitals WHEREAS, certain United States entities and Hydro-Quebec, a utility operating within the province of Quebec, Canada (“Hydro-Quebec”), have constructed the interconnection facilities required to interconnect the regional electric system in New England with the electric system of Hydro-Quebec; and WHEREAS, Phase I of the Interconnection consists of the United States portion of a +/- 450 kV high-voltage, direct current (“HVDC”) transmission line from a terminal at the Des Cantons Substation on the Hydro-Quebec system near Sherbrooke, Quebec to the location of the former terminal having had a nominal rating of 690 MW, which was adjacent to a substation at the location of the Comerford Generating Station on the Connecticut River (hereinafter referred to as Phase I). In October 2012, the Phase I terminal facilities were retired, and the substation interconnection was decommissioned, leaving the remaining Phase I HVDC facilities and equipment to be utilized solely with Phase II. The portion of Phase II in the United States consists of an extension of the Phase I HVDC transmission line from Phase I at the Comerford Generating Station location through New Hampshire to Sandy Pond in Ayer, Massachusetts, with additional HVDC terminal facilities installed at Sandy Pond that increased the prior transfer capacity from Hydro-Quebec to approximately 2,000 MW, when conditions permit, in accordance with Good Utility Practice; and WHEREAS, the Phase I IRH entered into the Phase I Support Agreements with respect to the financial support of the Phase I facilities; and the Phase II IRH entered into the Phase II Support Agreements with respect to the financial support of the Phase II facilities; and WHEREAS, the Phase I Support Agreements obligate the Phase I IRH to pay all of the costs of the Phase I facilities through payment of support charges to the companies that built, own, operate and maintain the United States portion of the Phase I facilities; viz., New England Electric Transmission Corporation and Vermont Electric Transmission Company; and WHEREAS, the Phase II Support Agreements obligate the Phase II IRH to pay all of the cost of the Phase II facilities through payment of support charges to the companies that built, own, operate and maintain the United States portion of the Phase II facilities; viz., New England Hydro-Transmission Electric Company, Inc. and New England Hydro-Transmission Corporation; and WHEREAS, in exchange for payment of the support charges, the Support Agreements provide that the IRH have exclusive rights to the use of the full capability of the Interconnection in accordance with this Use Agreement, the Support Agreements, and with their respective shares of the support costs; and WHEREAS, this Use Agreement is intended to further define the rights of the IRH to: use the Interconnection, make the rights available to others, provide for the collective management of those rights through a governance arrangement, and for the IRH Management Committee to serve as the Advisory Committee under the Support Agreements; and WHEREAS, the Use Agreement is one of the Basic Agreements that is integral to the IRH participation in the other Basic Agreements; and WHEREAS, the fundamental purposes of the Basic Agreements including this Agreement, are to provide for: (a) secure financial support for the costs of the Interconnection, and appropriate investment return for the owners of the assets; and (b) certain benefits to the IRH in return for their financial support for the Interconnection, including but not limited to: (i) transmission rights to the transmission transfer capability on the Interconnection between New England and Quebec up to the maximum transfer capability of 2,000 MW in accordance with Good Utility Practice; (ii) the ability to import and export energy, capacity and ancillary services between the ISO-NE and Hydro-Quebec transmission systems for commercial and reliability purposes, promoting economic and environmental benefits to customers in New England by facilitating the delivery of zero-carbon energy at a reasonable cost; and (iii) an operable Interconnection to allow for use of the Use Rights and to promote reliability and energy security related benefits to New England; and WHEREAS, the IRH have exercised their right to extend the Basic Agreements for an additional twenty year term and wish to make revisions to this Use Agreement appropriate for such extension; and WHEREAS, the IRH also wish to restate the Initial Agreement in this Fourth Amended and Restated Use Agreement; NOW THEREFORE, in consideration of the premises, the mutual covenants hereinafter set forth, and other good and valuable consideration, the receipt and sufficiency of which is hereby acknowledged, the IRH agree as follows:

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 1. Defined Terms. Whenever used in this Use Agreement, the following terms shall have the following respective meanings: 1.1 Basic Agreements shall mean the following agreements (as defined herein), each of which is coterminous with this Agreement: the Support Agreements, the Equity Funding Agreements and this Use Agreement. 1.2 Combined Percentage Interest shall have the meaning as defined in Section 3.7 of this Use Agreement and shall be as specified in Attachment A to this Use Agreement. 1.3 Emergency shall mean an abnormal condition on the bulk power system that if not immediately corrected could lead to the shedding of firm electrical load. Such abnormal conditions are sudden and unforeseen conditions and other conditions beyond the reasonable control and ability to avoid of the entity experiencing such conditions. 1.4 Emergency Energy shall mean energy that is exchanged between balancing authority area operators and delivered over the Interconnection from the Hydro-Quebec balancing authority area to the New England balancing authority area, or vice versa, in Emergencies. 1.5 Emergency Energy Transaction shall mean an allowed use of the Interconnection for the delivery of Emergency Energy in accordance with the provisions of this Use Agreement. 1.6 Entitlement Transaction shall mean any transaction utilizing the Interconnection allowed under this Use Agreement other than an Emergency Energy Transaction. 1.7 Equity Funding Agreements shall mean: (1) the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Electric Company, Inc., dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may be subsequently amended; and (2) the Amended and Restated Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Corporation, which amends and restates the Equity Funding Agreement for New England Hydro Transmission Corporation, dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated, May 1, 1986, September 1, 1987, and August 1, 1988, as it may subsequently be amended. 1.8 Good Utility Practice shall mean any of the practices, methods and acts engaged in or approved by a significant portion of the electric utility industry during the relevant time period, or any of the practices, methods and acts which, in the exercise of reasonable judgment in light of the facts known at the time the decision was made, could have been expected to accomplish the desired result at a reasonable cost consistent with good business practices, reliability, safety and expedition. Good Utility Practice is not intended to be limited to the optimum practice, method, or act to the exclusion of all others, but rather includes all acceptable practices, methods, or acts generally accepted in the region. 1.9 Hourly Transfer Capability shall mean the amount of energy which may be transferred over the Interconnection without violation of the alternating current power system operating criteria, as determined by ISO-NE, it being understood that the Interconnection may be limited due to HVDC equipment restrictions or power system constraints in the Hydro-Quebec TransEnergie, PJM or New York ISO balancing authority areas. Hourly Transfer Capability shall be as determined by ISO-NE. 1.10 Indirect IRH shall mean an entity that is not a Party to this Use Agreement but which acquires Use Rights in the Interconnection through a Transfer Agreement with one or more IRH. 1.11 Interconnection shall mean the Phase I and II HVDC interconnection, transmission and converter terminal facilities in the United States interconnecting the Hydro-Quebec TransEnergie system and the ISO-NE system, provided for and described in the Basic Agreements, with a nominal transfer capability of 2,000 MW. 1.12 Interconnection Rights Holder(s) (“IRH(s)”) shall mean one or more of the entities that are granted exclusive rights to the use of the Interconnection transmission capability under the Support Agreements in return for being financially obligated thereunder to pay for the costs of the Interconnection. 1.13 IRH Management Committee (“IMC”) shall mean the governance committee among the IRH provided for under this Use Agreement. The IMC also serves as the Advisory Committee under the Support Agreements. The IMC has the powers, governance, rights and responsibilities described in Section 5 of this Use Agreement and in the Support Agreements. 1.14 ISO-NE shall mean ISO New England Inc., the Independent System Operator and Regional Transmission Organization and balancing authority for New England, and any successor organization. 1.15 Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection shall have the meaning as defined in Section 3.7 of this Use Agreement. 1.16 OATT shall mean an open access transmission tariff subject to the jurisdiction of the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission. 1.17 Payment Agent is the entity designated by a vote of the IRH Management Committee to perform such functions and have such authority with respect to funds, payments, accounts, the management of the Use Rights, and financial matters related to this Use Agreement as the IRH Management Committee may determine in accordance with Section 10 of this Use Agreement. 1.18 Percentage Interest is the amount of Use Rights and related financial obligations specified in Attachment A to this Use Agreement. 1.19 Percentage Interest in Phase I and the Phase I Nominal Transfer Capability shall have the meaning as defined in Section 3 of this Use Agreement and shall be specified in Attachment A to this Use Agreement. 1.20 Percentage Interest in Phase II and the Phase II Nominal Transfer Capability shall have the meaning as defined in Section 3 of this Use Agreement and shall be specified in Attachment A to this Use Agreement. 1.21 Phase I shall mean the initial stage of the Interconnection in Vermont and New Hampshire, provided for and described in the Phase I Support Agreements. 1.22 Phase I Interconnection Rights Holder(s) (“Phase I IRH”) shall mean an entity or the entities which is/are obligated to pay the cost of the Phase I facilities under the Phase I Support Agreements. The entities that are Phase I IRH are listed in Attachment A to this Use Agreement. 1.23 Phase I Support Agreements shall mean: (i) the Amended and Restated Phase I New Hampshire Transmission Line Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase I Terminal Facility Support Agreement originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986, as it may be subsequently amended; and (ii) the Amended and Restated Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase I Vermont Transmission Line Support Agreement, originally dated December 1, 1981, with amendments dated June 1, 1982, November 1, 1982, and January 1, 1986, as it may be subsequently amended. 1.24 Phase II shall mean the subsequent stage of construction of the Interconnection, provided for and described in the Phase II Support Agreements, that augmented the nominal transfer capability of the Interconnection to 2000 MW through construction of an HVDC transmission line from the location of the Comerford Generating Station through New Hampshire to a new converter terminal facility adjacent to and interconnected with the Sandy Pond Substation in Ayer, Massachusetts. 1.25 Phase II Interconnection Rights Holder(s) (“Phase II IRH”) shall mean an entity or the entities which is/are obligated to pay the cost of the Phase II facilities under the Phase II Support Agreements. The entities that are Phase II IRH are listed in Attachment A hereto. 1.26 Phase II Support Agreements shall mean (i) the Amended and Restated Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement is Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase II Massachusetts Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, originally dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, and January 1, 1989, as it may be subsequently amended; and (ii) the Amended and Restated Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, which amends and restates the Phase II New Hampshire Transmission Facilities Support Agreement, originally dated June 1, 1985, with amendments dated May 1, 1986, February 1, 1987, June 1, 1987, September 1, 1987, October 1, 1987, August 1, 1988, January 1, 1989, and January 1, 1990, as it may be subsequently amended. 1.27 Schedule 20A Service Provider shall mean an individual IRH that offers its own Use Rights or the Use Rights of other IRHs under Schedule 20A to the ISO-NE OATT or successor tariff provisions. 1.28 Support Agreements shall mean the Phase I and Phase II Support Agreements. 1.29 Transfer Agreement shall mean those agreements for the transfer of the Use Rights as specified and provided for in Section 6 of this Use Agreement. 1.30 Transfer Capability of the Interconnection as used in Section 6 of this Use Agreement shall mean the Hourly Transfer Capability. 1.31 Use Rights shall mean the exclusive rights to use the transmission capacity of the Interconnection granted to the IRH under the Support Agreements in exchange for the financial commitment of the IRH to support the full costs of the Interconnection in accordance with the Support Agreements. The Use Rights are further provided for and governed by this Use Agreement.

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 2. Basic Understandings 2.1 The facilities covered under the Phase I and Phase II Support Agreements are integrally related and interdependent facilities, and the Parties intend that they be treated accordingly under the Basic Agreements. The Basic Agreements are intended to work together as a set of interrelated agreements governing participation in the Interconnection and the rights and obligations that result from such participation. 2.2 The Parties have made commitments under the Basic Agreements to obtain the benefits of the Interconnection, as further described in the recitals above. In connection with the benefits intended under the Basic Agreements, the parties also recognize certain other agreements and ISO-NE tariff provisions are important to the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements. These other agreements include: (i) a certain Asset Owners Agreement between the asset owners of the Interconnection facilities and the asset owners of the interconnected facilities in Quebec; (ii) the Interconnection Operators Agreement between the system operators in the United States and Quebec; (iii) the Phase II Maine Electric Power SVC Support Agreement between New England Hydro-Transmission Corp. and Maine Electric Power Company to provide for certain static var compensator facilities specified in that agreement important to the reliable operation of the Interconnection; (iv) the Transmission Service Administration Agreement among the IMC, ISO-NE and the Schedule 20A Service Providers to provide for administration of transmission service over the Interconnection; (v) the HVDC Transmission Operating Agreement among the Asset Owners and ISO-NE; (vi) certain agreements related to the improvements and reinforcements to AC transmission systems in Massachusetts necessitated by Phase II, and referred to as the “Phase II New England Power AC Facilities Support Agreement” and the “Phase II Boston Edison AC Facilities Support Agreement”; and (vii) the provisions of the ISO-NE tariff and any related rules and successor provisions that provide for HQ Interconnection Capability Credits (as defined in that tariff) or similar provisions for compensating the IRH for the reliability, fuel and energy security benefits of the Interconnection. The parties agree to act toward these other agreements and tariff provisions in such a way as to promote the intended benefits under the Basic Agreements.

record_data.record_title: IRH Shares; Transfer Capability of the Interconnection
record_data.record_plain_text: Section 3. Interconnection Rights Holders’ Shares; Transfer Capability of the Interconnection. 3.1 Under the Phase I Support Agreements the Phase I IRH are granted the exclusive right to use the Phase I facilities in accordance with this Use Agreement. Under the Phase II Support Agreements the Phase II IRH are granted the exclusive right to use the Phase II facilities in accordance with this Use Agreement. 3.2 In order to permit the use by all IRH and their transferees of Use Rights as provided for under Section 6 of this Use Agreement of both the Phase I and the Phase II facilities: (a) the Phase I IRH hereby grant to each Phase II IRH and those entities to whom the Phase II IRH transfers its rights or makes them available the right to use the Phase I facilities in accordance with this Use Agreement to the extent of each Phase II IRH’s Combined Percentage Interest, and (b) the Phase II IRH hereby grant to each Phase I IRH and those entities to whom the Phase I IRH transfers its rights or makes them available the right to use the Phase II facilities in accordance with this Use Agreement to the extent of the Phase I IRH’s Combined Percentage Interest. 3.3 The use by each IRH of either the Phase I facilities or the Phase II facilities shall be in common with all other IRH and no IRH in using its Combined Percentage Interest with respect to either the Phase I facilities or the Phase II facilities shall have priority over any other IRH in using its Combined Percentage Interest, except for such priority of scheduling and curtailing transactions using the Use Rights as may be established by relevant reliability authorities (e.g., the North American Electric Reliability Corporation and the Northeast Power Coordinating Council) and under such scheduling and curtailment rules as may be accepted and/or approved by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission for participation in the regional electricity markets. 3.4 The Percentage Interest in the Phase I Nominal Transfer Capability of each Phase I IRH is specified in Attachment A. Each Phase I IRH’s Percentage Interest in Phase I is currently equal to the share of the costs of the Phase I facilities which it supports under the Phase I Support Agreements. In the event a Phase I IRH’s support share under the Phase I Support Agreements is modified or terminated in accordance with the provisions of the Phase I Support Agreements, its Percentage Interest in Phase I shall automatically be adjusted by the same amount or terminated, as appropriate, (and the Percentage Interests in Phase I of the continuing Phase I IRH shall automatically be adjusted to equal their respective percentages as adjusted in accordance with the provisions of the Phase I Support Agreements) as of the time that such adjustment or termination becomes effective under the Phase I Support Agreements. 3.5 The Percentage Interest in the Phase II Nominal Transfer Capability of each Phase II IRH is specified in Attachment A. Each Phase II IRH’s Percentage Interest in Phase II is equal to the share of the costs of the Phase II facilities which it supports under the Phase II Support Agreements. In the event a Phase II IRH’s support share under the Phase II Support Agreements is modified or terminated in accordance with the provisions of the Phase II Support Agreements, its Percentage Interest in Phase II shall automatically be adjusted by the same amount or terminated, as appropriate, (and the Percentage Interests in Phase II of the continuing Phase II IRH shall automatically be adjusted to equal their respective percentages as adjusted in accordance with the provisions of the Phase II Support Agreements) as of the time that such adjustment or termination becomes effective under the Phase II Support Agreements. 3.6 In the event of the complete termination of an IRH’s status as an IRH under the Support Agreements and under this Use Agreement, its rights to use the Interconnection and all of its other rights under this Use Agreement shall cease, as of the effective time of such termination. 3.7 An IRH’s Combined Percentage Interest is the percentage of the Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection represented by the following fraction: the sum, in megawatts, of (a) its Percentage Interest in Phase I times the Phase I Nominal Transfer Capability, plus (b) its Percentage Interest in Phase II times the Phase II Nominal Transfer Capability, divided by the Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection. The Combined Percentage Interest of each IRH is specified in Attachment A. The “Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection” is 2,000 MW. The “Phase I Nominal Transfer Capability” is 690 MW. The “Phase II Nominal Transfer Capability” is 1,310 MW, which is the difference between the total Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection (2,000 MW) and the Phase I Nominal Transfer Capability (690 MW). The Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection and the Phase I and Phase II Nominal Transfer Capability shall be subject to review by the IRH Management Committee, and shall be subject to modification by the IRH Management Committee if after review that committee determines in good faith that there has been a substantial change in the Interconnection facilities or their operation justifying such modification. To the extent that the IRH Management Committee makes such a modification, it shall do so in accordance with this Use Agreement and any applicable provisions of the Support Agreements.

record_data.record_title: Effective Date; Term; Effect on Existing Agreements
record_data.record_plain_text: Section 4. Effective Date; Term; Effect on Existing Agreements. 4.1 This Use Agreement shall become effective on January 1, 2021, or upon such other date as the Use Agreement is permitted to go into effect by the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission (the “Effective Date”). 4.2 No modification or termination of this Use Agreement or of an IRH’s status shall relieve any party of any obligation arising prior to the Effective Date of such modification or termination. In addition, notwithstanding the termination of this Use Agreement for other purposes, this Use Agreement shall continue in effect to the extent necessary to provide for final billings, billing adjustments, payments and any other necessary matters of administration. 4.3 Notwithstanding the effectiveness of this Use Agreement, the rights, duties, obligations, and liabilities of the Indirect IRH listed in Attachment A shall not be terminated but shall continue in accordance with this Use Agreement. 4.4 The term of this Agreement will expire or otherwise terminate when the Support Agreements expire or otherwise terminate, including under any renewal terms of those agreements.

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 5. IRH Management Committee. 5.1 There shall be an IRH Management Committee which shall have the duty and requisite authority to: (a) administer, enforce, and recommend amendments to the provisions of this Use Agreement (subject to Section 12 of this Use Agreement); (b) represent the IRH collectively in regulatory, judicial and/or other proceedings related to this Use Agreement, the other Basic Agreements and the Interconnection; (c) to perform such additional duties as may from time-to-time be assigned to it by mutual agreement of IRH having Combined Percentage Interests aggregating at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent, to act as further provided for below; and (d) to exercise such additional authority and carry such additional responsibilities as are set forth in Section 5.12 of this Use Agreement. The IMC shall also serve as the Advisory Committee to the Asset Owners under the Support Agreements, and shall have such additional authority, rights and responsibilities as are provided for in those agreements. 5.2 Only the IRH shall have membership and voting rights in the IMC, except that, if an IRH expressly transfers its voting rights to an Indirect IRH pursuant to a Transfer Agreement and provides written notice of the transfer of such voting rights to the Secretary of the IMC, then the Indirect IRH who is the transferee may also have membership and voting rights in the IMC in accordance with this Use Agreement and the Transfer Agreement for the duration of the transfer of such voting rights. The Secretary of the IMC shall promptly circulate any such notice received to all members of the IMC. 5.3 Each IRH shall appoint and be represented by, and each Indirect IRH may appoint and be represented by, one member and one alternate member of the IMC. Each member of the IMC appointed by an IRH or an Indirect IRH shall hold office until such member is replaced by the IRH or Indirect IRH that appointed the member or until such IRH or Indirect IRH ceases to be an IRH or an Indirect IRH, as the case may be. Replacement of a member shall be effected by delivery by an IRH or an Indirect IRH of written notice of such replacement to the Secretary of the IMC. 5.4 An IRH, an Indirect IRH may designate, by written notice delivered to the Secretary of the IMC, an alternate for any member of the IMC appointed by it. In the absence of the member, the alternate shall have all the powers of the member, including the power to vote. An IRH or Indirect IRH may allow another IRH or Indirect IRH to cast votes on its behalf pursuant to a written proxy provided to the Secretary of the IMC in advance of the vote in which the proxy is to be exercised. A member or alternate may designate another person to serve as proxy for such member or alternate pursuant to a written proxy provided to the Secretary of the IMC in advance of the meeting in which the proxy is to be exercised. 5.5 If two or more IRH or Indirect IRH so elect, they may designate a single member or alternate member to represent them. All designations and changes in designations of members and alternate members shall be in writing and shall be delivered to the Secretary of the IMC and filed with the records of the IMC. 5.6 Voting on the IMC shall be by Combined Percentage Interest, with each member having a vote equal to the Combined Percentage Interest of the IRH or Indirect IRH whom he or she represents. For purposes of voting on the IMC, the Combined Percentage Interest of each IRH and Indirect IRH shall be calculated when necessary, stated on a monthly basis in a voting spreadsheet or other document by the Secretary of the IMC as part of the IMC meeting materials. The Combined Percentage Interest contained in such a document shall be the Combined Percentage Interest for purposes of voting on the IMC in that month. Where a member represents multiple IRH or Indirect IRH, that member may vote separately the respective Combined Percentage Interests of each IRH or Indirect IRH. 5.7 For an action to be adopted by the IMC, a vote of members representing IRH or Indirect IRH having aggregate Combined Percentage Interests of at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent is required, provided that action which affects only Phase I IRH and Phase I Indirect IRH shall require only the vote of members representing Phase I IRH and Phase I Indirect IRH having Percentage Interests in Phase I aggregating at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent of the total Phase I Percentage Interests, and provided further that action which affects only Phase II IRH and Phase II Indirect IRH shall require only the vote of members representing Phase II IRH and Phase II Indirect IRH having Percentage Interests in Phase II aggregating at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent of the total Phase II Percentage Interests. 5.8 The IMC shall elect annually from its members a Chair and a Vice Chair; the IMC shall also elect annually a Secretary who need not be a member. These officers shall have the powers and duties usually incident to such offices. If an officer cannot complete its term, the IMC shall take appropriate steps to promptly replace the officer. 5.9 The IMC shall hold its meetings in accordance with a schedule adopted by the IMC or at the call of the Chair. One or more members who represent IRH or Indirect IRH having Combined Percentage Interests of at least 10% may call a special meeting of the IMC in the event that the Chair shall fail to call such a meeting within three business days following the Chair’s receipt from such member or members of a request specifying the subject matters to be acted upon at a meeting. 5.10 Written notice of each meeting of the IMC shall be given (via electronic means or otherwise) to each member and each alternate not less than three business days prior to the date of the meeting, which notice shall specify the principal subject matter expected to be acted upon at the meeting. 5.11 The IMC may adopt by-laws, consistent with this Section 5, governing procedural matters including the conduct of its meetings. 5.12 In addition to the general authority granted to or assumed by the IMC as provided above, the IMC’s authority shall include the authority, to be exercised in accordance with this Use Agreement, to: (a) negotiate, enter into, administer, and enforce agreements on behalf of the IRH and Indirect IRH collectively, provided that such agreements have been approved by the IMC by a vote of members representing IRH or Indirect IRH having in aggregate Combined Percentage Interests of at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent; (b) represent the collective position of the IRH in legal or regulatory proceedings, including before the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, provided that such collective position shall be determined by a vote of members representing IRH or Indirect IRH having aggregate Combined Percentage Interests of at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent, or in the case of exigent circumstances, when there is not time for IMC consideration and vote, by the concurrence of the IMC officers with advance notice to the IMC; (c) act as liaison with other entities regarding matters affecting the collective rights and obligations and interests of the IRH, including, but not limited to, with such entities as the asset owners of the Phase I and Phase II facilities, the ISO and other system operators and regional transmission organization(s), the New England Power Pool, state regulators, Hydro-Quebec entities, and the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission and its staff; and (d) by a vote of members representing IRH or Indirect IRH having aggregate Combined Percentage Interests of at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent, engage the services of consultants, legal counsel, a Payment Agent and other service providers to assist the IMC and the IRH collectively. 5.13 The costs of the activities of the IMC, including, but not limited to, its use of legal, consulting or Payment Agent services, shall be paid through the Support Charges under the Support Agreements and shall be allocated to all of the IRH on a Combined Percentage Interest basis.

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 6. Use of the Interconnection. 6.1 Subject only to the other provisions of this Section, each Participant shall individually have the right to use all or any portion of its Percentage Interest in the Transfer Capability of the Interconnection for Entitlement Transactions without any restriction. 6.2 Commercial transactions over the Interconnection, either for imports into New England or exports out of New England, may be conducted only by the IRH (either independently or collectively or by a scheduling agent) or by entities who have acquired Use Rights from the IRH pursuant to this Section 6, Schedule 20A of the ISO-NE OATT, any other applicable OATT provision(s). In Emergencies and pursuant to Section 7.1 of this Use Agreement, ISO-NE may conduct Emergency Energy Transactions over the Interconnection. 6.3 Each IRH shall individually have the right to use or make available to eligible transmission customers all or any portion of its Combined Percentage Interest of the Nominal Transfer Capability. Entitlement Transactions shall be subject to the rules for scheduling and curtailing transactions applied to transactions in the regional electricity markets, and as provided for under Section 3.3 of this Use Agreement. In the regional real-time energy market, to the extent that, in any given hour, (i) a Use Rights holder has a scheduled transaction and (ii) it has used up its Combined Percentage Interest as applied to the Hourly Transfer Capability, and (iii) there is unused capacity still available on the Interconnection, then that Use Rights holder may use that unused capacity for that transaction up to the limit of the Combined Percentage Interest of the Nominal Transfer Capability represented by the Use Rights it holds. 6.4 The net MW amount of all commercial transactions over the Interconnection using the Use Rights of a given IRH in any hour, either for a net flow of imports into New England or net flow of exports out of New England for that IRH, shall always be limited to the Combined Percentage Interest of that IRH times the Hourly Transfer Capability of the Interconnection in the direction of that IRH's net flow over the Interconnection. 6.5 Each IRH may transfer or make available its Use Rights, or any portion of those rights, for a specified period of time either: (a) through a Transfer Agreement as described below in this Section 6, or (b) by making its Use Rights available to eligible transmission customers through an OATT and over an OATT administrator’s Open Access Same-Time Information System (“OASIS”), including through Schedule 20A to the ISO-NE OATT. To the extent that an IRH makes its Use Rights available under an OATT and on OASIS, it shall disclose to eligible customers applicable limitations on those rights imposed under this Use Agreement and the Support Agreements. 6.6 Each IRH shall have the right to enter into an agreement with another entity for the transfer of its Use Rights (a “Transfer Agreement”) to permit all or part of the IRH’s Combined Percentage Interest to be used by the other entity (the “Transferee”, which for the period of the transfer becomes an Indirect IRH), or otherwise transacted with by the Transferee, including through additional Transfer Agreements, for a specified period of time of not less than one full calendar day. Transferees may also enter into Transfer Agreements with third party Transferees. A Transfer Agreement is the only means by which an IRH may transfer its voting rights on the IMC to another entity. No Transfer Agreement shall operate to relieve the original transferring IRH (“Transferor”) of its obligations under this Use Agreement without the written consent of the other parties hereto. A Transfer Agreement may be on such terms as the Transferor determines, except that the Transfer Agreement shall contain provisions to the effect that: (a) the parties to the Transfer Agreement shall provide advance notice of the transfer, and such other information as may be necessary for the administration of the Use Rights, to ISO-NE, or such other entity as may be administering the Use Rights, and to the IMC through its Secretary; (b) whenever the Transferee receives written notice that the Transferor has failed to perform any obligation under any of the Support Agreements and for so long as such failure continues, the Transferee shall thereafter make all its payments under the Transfer Agreement to the Payment Agent as designated by the IMC; (c) whenever the Transferee receives written notice that the Transferor’s participation has been terminated pursuant to the Phase I Support Agreements or Phase II Support Agreements, or both, and effective as of the time at which such termination becomes effective, the Transferee shall thereafter make its payments under the Transfer Agreement to the other IRH in such percentages as are specified in such notice; (d) in the event that the Transfer Agreement is for a term exceeding one year and the amount payable by the Transferee pursuant to the Transfer Agreement for the portion of the Nominal Transfer Capability of the Interconnection covered by the Transfer Agreement is less than the amount of the support charges for such portion under the Support Agreements, the Transferee shall, upon its receipt of the notice provided for under (b) above, and effective as of the time at which the termination of the Transferor’s participation pursuant to the Phase I Support Agreements or Phase II Support Agreements, or both, becomes effective, be obligated to increase its payments under the Transfer Agreement to cover in full such support charges under the Support Agreements in question unless it elects to terminate the Transfer Agreement; and (e) the Transfer Agreement shall provide that the Transferee shall be bound to the terms and conditions of this Use Agreement as an Indirect IRH. 6.7 To the extent that an IRH or Indirect IRH relies on ISO-NE or another entity to administer transactions over the Interconnection, including, but not limited to, the transfer and/or scheduling of its Use Rights that IRH or Indirect IRH shall comply with the administrative requirements of that administrator, including any applicable provisions of the Transmission Service Administration Agreement among ISO-NE, the IMC and the Schedule 20A Service Providers. 6.8 The IRH, through the IMC, shall cooperate with ISO-NE and other Independent System Operators and Regional Transmission Organization(s) in the Northeast to coordinate the use of the Interconnection in accordance with this Use Agreement with other Independent System Operator and Regional Transmission Organization rules so as to facilitate regional energy transactions; provided, that such cooperation and coordination shall not impair the Use Rights that have been granted to the IRH and that are paid for by the IRH under the Support Agreements.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_title: Use Rights Availability for Emergency Energy Transactions
record_data.record_plain_text: Section 7. Use Rights Availability for Emergency Energy Transactions. 7.1 In the event of an Emergency, when their Use Rights are not being used for actual flows of energy, the IRH and Indirect IRH shall make their Use Rights available to ISO-NE for Emergency Energy Transactions; provided that, the IRH shall be entitled to seek compensation for the use of such rights in accordance with the terms, conditions and rates of the appropriate open access transmission tariff or other filed rate. Such compensation shall be effected under a separate agreement or agreements between ISO-NE, the IRH and any other necessary party or parties, or through other Federal Energy Regulatory Commission-approved tariff provisions.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 8. Transmission Service. 8.1 It is recognized that Emergency Energy Transactions and an IRH’s Entitlement Transactions may require the use of the transmission facilities of other IRH that are transmission owners and/or providers to effect deliveries to or from the Interconnection terminal facilities. Accordingly, the IRH that are transmission owners and/or providers shall effect such deliveries over their own transmission systems to the extent that doing so would not diminish the reliability of such systems and to the extent that capacity is physically available. The entity using the transmission facilities of other IRH shall do so in accordance with the terms, conditions and rates of the appropriate OATT or other filed rate. In the event no filed rate covers the transaction, the IRH that is the transmission owner and/or provider with respect to the facilities being used shall provide such a rate upon request. Each IRH that is a transmission owner and/or provider agrees to use commercially reasonable efforts to provide, to the extent necessary, adequate transmission services from the Interconnection terminal facilities to the electric utility systems of other IRH that are transmission owners and/or providers in accordance with applicable OATTs. Accordingly, each IRH that is a transmission owner and/or provider shall cooperate with all other IRH that are transmission owners and/or providers in a good faith effort, consistent with Good Utility Practice, to resolve any limitation(s) on providing such transmission services.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 9. Relationship among the IRH. 9.1 The obligations of the IRH are several and not joint. Any intent to create by this Use Agreement, or by any activity related hereto, an association, joint venture, trust, or partnership rights or obligations is expressly negated. Except as expressly provided in this Use Agreement, no IRH shall have by virtue of this Use Agreement, or of any such activity, the right or power to bind any other IRH without its express written consent.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 10. Payment Agent. 10.1 The IMC may designate and determine the specific functions of a Payment Agent to act on behalf of the IRH with respect to: (a) the collection, holding and disbursement of funds related to Transfer Agreements, as specified in Section 6 of this Use Agreement, and (b) the collective management, if any, of the Use Rights. To the extent that payments are called for under Transfer Agreements as a result of a Transferor’s failure to meet obligations under the Support Agreements, such payments shall be made to the Payment Agent. The Payment Agent shall serve under the supervision of the IMC officers. 10.2 The Payment Agent shall be paid such fees for its services hereunder as shall be agreed to by the Payment Agent and the IMC. The Payment Agent’s fees shall be allocated among the IRH in accordance with their respective Combined Percentage Interests. 10.3 In the event questions arise as to the exercise of the Payment Agent’s functions hereunder, the Payment Agent shall be entitled to request and rely upon the instructions of the IMC. The IRH shall indemnify the Payment Agent for, and hold it harmless against, any loss, liability, or expense incurred (except as may be attributable to the gross negligence or willful misconduct of the Payment Agent) arising out of this Use Agreement. The Payment Agent shall be liable only for its own gross negligence or willful misconduct and shall incur no liability for action in accordance with the terms of this Use Agreement or with the terms of any instructions received by it from the IMC. 10.4 The Payment Agent may resign at any time by giving thirty days advance written notice to the Secretary of the IMC, or may be removed by the IMC at will upon the IMC giving the Payment Agent thirty days advance written notice. In the event of such a resignation or removal, the IMC may appoint a new Payment Agent, which shall be entitled to receive all of the records and funds then held by the predecessor Payment Agent.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 11. Successors and Assigns. 11.1 This Use Agreement shall be binding upon and shall inure to the benefit of, and may be performed by, the successors and assigns of the parties, and shall also be binding, insofar as permitted by law, on any receiver or trustee in bankruptcy, receivership, or reorganization of any party. Except for a sale, merger, consolidation or involuntary transfer which results in the transfer of substantially all of an IRH’s assets to, and the assumption of all of the IRH’s obligations hereunder by, an electric utility or other entity which is a member of the New England Power Pool (or its successor entity), no assignment or partial assignment of this Use Agreement shall operate to relieve the assignor of its obligations under this Use Agreement without the written consent of the other parties hereto, which consent shall not be unreasonably withheld. Written notice to the IMC through its Secretary shall be given by an IRH prior to any assignment or partial assignment by it hereunder, and the IMC Secretary shall promptly notify the IMC of any such received notice of assignment.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 12. Amendments. 12.1 Any amendment changing the percentage shares of the IRH in the use of the Interconnection or revising Sections 6.1 – 6.7 of this Use Agreement shall require the written agreement of all parties to this Use Agreement. All other amendments to this Use Agreement may be made by mutual agreement of the IRH having Combined Percentage Interests aggregating at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent, and shall be evidenced by a written amendment signed by such IRH, provided that an amendment which affects only Phase I IRH shall require only the agreement of Phase I IRH having Percentage Interests in Phase I aggregating at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent, and that an amendment which affects only Phase II IRH shall require only the agreement of Phase II IRH having Percentage Interests in Phase II aggregating at least sixty-six and two-thirds percent. Any such amendment shall become effective as to all IRH on the date specified in the amendment, whether or not the remaining IRH agree, provided that such an amendment does not impose a burden on the remaining affected IRH which is materially different in nature or materially greater in degree than that imposed on the affected IRH which have agreed to such amendment.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 13. Notices. 13.1 Except as the parties may otherwise agree, any notice, request, payment, or other communication from one party to the others, relating to this Use Agreement, or the rights, obligations or performance of the parties hereunder, shall be in writing and shall be delivered electronically to the IRH at the electronic mail address of its member on the IMC or to the Secretary of the IMC with a request to forward it to the appropriate member(s) of that committee. Any notice or other communication to the IMC required under this Use Agreement shall be sent to the Secretary of the IMC. Any such communication delivered electronically shall be deemed given when received by the intended recipient.

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 14. Governing Law. 14.1 This Use Agreement shall be governed by and construed in accordance with the laws of the Commonwealth of Massachusetts.
record_data.filing_title: Use Agreement Baseline and Compliance Filing

record_data.record_plain_text: Section 15. Arbitration. 15.1 In the event any IRH is aggrieved by an action taken, or any failure to act, under the provisions of this Use Agreement, the IRH shall first raise its grievance with the IMC and act in good faith to try to resolve the issue. If that attempt fails the aggrieved IRH shall be entitled to require that the matter be submitted for arbitration, in accordance with the provisions of this Section, to the American Arbitration Association (“AAA”) for mandatory binding arbitration under the AAA Commercial Arbitration Rules, as modified below. 15.2 If an IRH desires to require submission to arbitration of any matter in accordance with this Section, it shall first present the matter in writing to the IMC. If this matter is not satisfactorily resolved within twenty days of the submission of the matter to the IMC, the aggrieved IRH may submit the matter to the AAA for arbitration, and shall give a signed and written notice of submission to arbitration, specifying particularly the matter to be submitted to arbitration, to the Secretary of the IMC who shall inform all of the IRH. At the same time, the IRH shall mail a copy of the request to each other IMC member. Any other IRH which desires to be a party to the arbitration proceeding shall give to the IMC a signed and written notice within ten days of its receipt of the notice of arbitration. 15.3 A single neutral arbitrator shall be appointed. The parties to the proceeding shall attempt in good faith to agree on the arbitrator to be appointed. If an agreement is not reached on the arbitrator within thirty days after the notice of submission to arbitration is given to the IMC, the IMC shall, at the request of any party, apply to the American Arbitration Association for appointment of the arbitrator. The arbitrator shall be a disinterested person who has technical qualifications in the area of the matter in dispute and experience in the electric utility industry. Unless the parties to the proceeding otherwise agree, the arbitrator shall conduct the proceeding in accordance with and subject to the rules of the American Arbitration Association Commercial Arbitration Rules and shall render his decision with respect to the matter in controversy as promptly as practicable. The arbitrator shall be authorized only to interpret and apply the provisions of this Agreement and shall have no power to modify or change this Agreement in any manner. The decision of the arbitrator shall be final and binding upon all. The arbitrator’s decision shall be in writing and contain reasons for the decision. The arbitrator shall direct in what manner the expenses of the proceeding will be borne. 15.4 The IMC may elect to be a party in any arbitration proceeding under this Section. 15.5 The site of the arbitration shall be Boston, Massachusetts, or such virtual location as may be agreed to by the Parties. The Parties may agree to conduct a virtual arbitration in accordance with the practices and procedures of the American Arbitration Association and any applicable law.

record_data.record_plain_text:
Section 16. Miscellaneous Provisions. 16.1 No action, regardless of form, arising out of this Use Agreement may be brought by any party hereto more than two years after the cause of action has arisen. 16.2 In the event that any clause or provision of this Use Agreement or any part thereof shall be declared invalid by any court, regulatory agency or other governmental authority having jurisdiction, such invalidity shall not affect the validity or enforceability of the remaining portions of this Use Agreement, and the Parties shall cooperate to replace the invalidated provision with a valid provision that carries out the intent of the Parties. 16.3 Any cost or charge reasonably incurred by the IMC pursuant to Section 5 of this Use Agreement to file, administer, enforce or implement this Use Agreement and the Use Rights collectively, including any costs associated with contracts for goods or services obtained on behalf of the IRH, shall be paid by the IRH in accordance with their respective Combined Percentage Interests in accordance with the provisions for Support Charges under the Support Agreements. 16.4 Each IRH and Indirect IRH shall, subject to appropriate non-disclosure agreements or other confidentiality protections, upon the request of any other IRH, Indirect IRH, ISO-NE, or the IMC, provide any documents and information, or otherwise cooperate, as reasonably required to implement any provisions of this Use Agreement.
16.5 Any number of counterparts of this Agreement may be executed, each of which shall have the same force and effect as the original and all of which, when taken together, will be deemed to constitute one and the same agreement. The exchange of copies of this Agreement and of signature pages by facsimile or other electronic transmission (including, without limitation, by exchange of electronic signatures and/or electronically mailed PDFs) shall constitute effective execution and delivery of this Agreement as to the Parties and may be used in lieu of the original Agreement for all purposes. Signatures of the Parties transmitted by facsimile or other electronic means shall be deemed to be their original signatures for all purposes. In proving this Agreement it shall not be necessary to produce or account for more than one such counterpart signed by the Party against whom enforcement is sought. 16.6 This Use Agreement, together with the other Basic Agreements, shall constitute the entire understanding among the Parties and shall supersede any and all previous understandings pertaining to the subject matter of this Use Agreement. 16.7 This Use Agreement is the corporate act and obligation of the parties hereto, and any claim hereunder against any shareholder, director, officer, official, employee, member or agent of any Party, as such, is expressly waived.
